        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 12:51:31.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nI'm good with this as is - these messages are annoying. But I'm wondering if we should pull into a configuration file?? Or use logback.xml to remove them?? Hardcoding in the JUnits is one thing, but for production maybe there's a remote chance they need to be put back on for debugging??. Perhaps its ok and too much work for little return, what do you folks think?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "042465d9afb04ee0758e5837d1dd1ff8ca6454a1",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1441,
          "name": "Chenfei Gao",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "cgao@research.att.com",
          "username": "cgao"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 13:09:09.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "c16131a86b1ec92a66e1130e337bcec145613428",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-08-13 13:23:18.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n> I'm good with this as is - these messages are annoying. But I'm\n > wondering if we should pull into a configuration file?? Or use\n > logback.xml to remove them?? Hardcoding in the JUnits is one thing,\n > but for production maybe there's a remote chance they need to be\n > put back on for debugging??. Perhaps its ok and too much work for\n > little return, what do you folks think?\n\nI agree with Pam, Bilal.   It's better to put them in the logback.xml those jetty packages that should be turned off.  Note that modifications to the logback.xml will take effect after some small delay.  That way, if you need debugging and turn on those messages, you can do on the fly in the lab without programmatic changes.   Otherwise, you'll have to build another image.   I suggest to identify those messages that are annoying, get the package, and set the log level in the logback.xml at the ERROR level.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
